					</th>\r\n					<th>\r\n						Provider\r\n					</th>\r\n					<th>\r\n						Link\r\n					</th>\r\n				</tr>\r\n			</thead>\r\n			<tbody>\r\n				<tr>\r\n					<td>\r\n						JDK\r\n					</td>\r\n					<td>\r\n						Oracle Corporation\r\n					</td>\r\n					<td>\r\n						<a target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://www.java.com/en/download/manual.jsp\">Download</a>\r\n					</td>\r\n				</tr>\r\n				<tr>\r\n					<td>\r\n						OpenJDK\r\n					</td>\r\n					<td>\r\n						Open Source\r\n					</td>\r\n					<td>\r\n						<a target=\"_blank\" href=\"http://openjdk.java.net/\">Download</a>\r\n					</td>\r\n				</tr>\r\n			</tbody>\r\n		</table>\r\n	</div>\r\n</div>\r\n<h5>\r\n    JDK Installation\r\n</h5>\r\n<hr/>\r\n<p>\r\n    JDK installation on Windows is a fairly simple process.\r\n</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n    <li>Run the installer</li>\r\n    <li>Accept the license agreement</li>\r\n    <li>Select an appropriate directory</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h5>\r\n    System Environment variables\r\n</h5>\r\n<hr/>\r\n<p>\r\n    Even when Java is successfully installed in your system, certain variables are necessary to be set in order for other \r\n    Java dependent applications to run correctly. JDK sets <code>JAVA_HOME</code> variable to\r\n    the path to the installation directory of Java automatically.\r\n</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	Assume that Java is installed at <code>C:\\Program Files\\Java\\jdk1.8.0_171</code>. \r\n    Search for \'environment variables\' in the start menu or control panel to edit using GUI or \r\n    enter the following commands in command line :\r\n</p>\r\n<h6>\r\n    JAVA_HOME\r\n</h6>\r\n<p>\r\n    <code>JAVA_HOME</code> informs other applications about the location of installation directory of Java.\r\n</p>\r\n<pre><code class=\"language-none\">setx JAVA_HOME \"C:\\Program Files\\Java\\jdk1.8.0_171\"</code></pre>\r\n<h6>\r\n    JRE_HOME\r\n</h6>\r\n<p>\r\n    <code>JRE_HOME</code> is path to JRE installation directory. If JDK is installed, JRE is generally inside the JDK.\r\n</p>\r\n<pre><code class=\"language-none\">setx JRE_HOME \"C:\\Program Files\\Java\\jdk1.8.0_171\\jre\"</code></pre>\r\n<h6>\r\n    PATH\r\n</h6>\r\n<p>\r\n    <code>PATH</code> tells the location of binary archives to command line from any directory.\r\n</p>\r\n<pre><code class=\"language-none\">setx PATH \"%PATH%;C:\\Program Files\\Java\\jdk1.8.0_171\\bin;\"</code></pre>','2018-04-30 12:38:49','2018-04-30 12:38:49'),('javafundamentals-introduction','Introduction',1,'final','tutorial','<p>\r\n    Java is one of the most popular general purpose programming language as well as a software platform, \r\n	developed by Sun Microsystems, later acquired by the Oracle Corporation. \r\n</p>\r\n<p>\r\n    Java is an object oriented language and has a large class library, or the Java API that defines most commonly used classes and functions. \r\n	A Java program runs on a virtual machine (JVM) which itself runs on the underlying operating system as a process. \r\n	The JVM and JRE has many procedures implemented in C/C++, which makes it a high level programming language.\r\n</p>\r\n<h5>\r\n    Why Java?\r\n</h5>\r\n<hr/>\r\n<p> \r\n	Java programs are run by the Java Virtual Machine (JVM) and not directly by the operating system. This unique feature of Java gives \r\n	the virtual machine better control over the execution of java programs, which gives various advantages over other programming languages.\r\n	Some of them are :\r\n</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n    <li>\r\n		<p>\r\n			<b>Portable : </b> Java applications are compiled to java byte code which then runs on the JVM. These compiled applications can\r\n			run on any machine (independent of the architecture) which has a JRE installed, like Windows, Linux, Mac/OS, etc. This makes Java \r\n			a highly portable software platform.\r\n		</p>\r\n    </li>\r\n    <li>\r\n		<p>\r\n			<b>Easy : </b> Java uses an object oriented approach, which makes it easy to program large applications and also \r\n			understand the existing ones from their source code (also equally important).\r\n		</p>\r\n    </li>\r\n    <li>\r\n		<p>\r\n			<b>Performance : </b> Java byte code is interpreted by JIT compiler in the runtime which is a process overhead but java still runs \r\n			fast as the java byte codes are very close to native codes. However, lower level languages like C, C++ will run faster.\r\n		</p>\r\n    </li>\r\n    <li>\r\n		<p>\r\n			<b>Robust : </b> If designed correctly using it\'s built-in features like exception handling, \r\n			Java applications are prone to crashes and unexpected runtime behaviors.\r\n		</p>\r\n    </li>\r\n    <li>\r\n		<p>\r\n			<b>Secure : </b> Java programs runs on it\'s virtual machine that itself runs as a process on the underlying operating system, \r\n			which makes interference from external processes (possibly viruses) very difficult. JVM has it\'s own memory manager or \r\n			the runtime data area, which checks for illegal memory access, followed by the operating system. \r\n			Also Java does not allow explicit pointers to addresses which makes it a very secure computing platform.\r\n		</p>\r\n    </li>\r\n    <li>\r\n		<p>\r\n			<b>Multi-threaded : </b> The JVM is programmed to execute threads concurrently. Programmers are allowed to create new threads in a java program. \r\n			Many applications these days require concurrent execution of tasks.\r\n		</p>\r\n    </li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p> \r\n	Various open source libraries and frameworks with solution to common problems are available developed by the java developer community.\r\n	These libraries are robust, secure and easy to use and are widely accepted by enterprises and other developers. Some of them are :\r\n</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n    <li>\r\n		<p>\r\n			<b>Graphical Interface : </b> Libraries like AWT, Swing are used to create graphical user interface objects like windows, buttons, etc. \r\n			These libraries are helpful for applications like computer games.\r\n		</p>\r\n    </li>\r\n    <li>\r\n		<p>\r\n			<b>Networking : </b> Java can be used for socket programming to send data to a given IP address at a port or listen to data \r\n			being received on a port. Various libraries in Java allow easy development and deployment of applications like web services, web-sites etc.\r\n		</p>\r\n    </li>\r\n    <li>\r\n		<p>\r\n			<b>Database : </b> Many applications need to operate on large amount of data at runtime stored in secondary memory. This management of \r\n			data can get difficult using traditional file operations, and database systems are used instead. Java provides JDBC driver for \r\n			almost all database management solutions like MySQL, Oracle, MongoDB, etc.\r\n		</p>\r\n    </li>\r\n</ul>','2018-04-30 12:33:58','2018-04-30 12:33:58'),('javafundamentals-objects-and-classes','Objects and Classes',1,'final','tutorial','<p>\r\n	Creating a <i>Programming Language</i> for a computer is exactly like teaching a machine, how to think. The creators of Java used \r\n	the concept of objects and classes, which is close to how humans think. Everything we see like a car, house, a chair or any person, \r\n	we consider them as <b>objects</b>. Each object is recognized by it\'s features and parameters, \r\n	while they all have a set of functions or tasks to perform.\r\n</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	We can classify these objects into various categories or <b>classes</b>, like all objects that are \"Chairs\" will have same kind of features \r\n	and functions, where as all objects that are \"Houses\" will have other. While programming we only record the set of features as well as functions\r\n	that our application requires.\r\n</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	Writing a Java program is nothing but defining a bunch of classes with variables (the features) and functions that may refer to each other. \r\n	Also there is a set of a few types of data that the language understands, will be discussed later.\r\n	In a Java program, we define classes in a particular syntax and objects of classes can be created at runtime.\r\n	Refer to the following example :\r\n</p>\r\n<pre><code class=\"language-java\">public class Car {\r\n	Integer cost; //variable\r\n	String color; //variable\r\n	\r\n	//function\r\n	public void drive(String destination, Integer velocity) {\r\n		//drive the car\r\n	}\r\n}</code></pre>\r\n\r\n<h5>Functions</h5>\r\n<hr/>\r\n<p>\r\n	Functions in a class contains a procedure to do a particular task. They may accept parameter values to perform the task, which\r\n	are provided at the runtime when the method is called. A function may also return a value to the caller at the runtime.\r\n	In the above example the <code>void</code> keyword shows that the particular function does not return any value.\r\n</p>\r\n\r\n<h5>Variables</h5>\r\n<hr/>\r\n<p>\r\n	A variable is a unit of data in Java. A variable can have a type (like character, integer, etc) or may refer to an entirely different object.\r\n	Variables can be classified according to the position of their location in a class.\r\n</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n    <li>\r\n		<p>\r\n			<b>Local variables</b> : Variables defined inside methods are called local variables. \r\n			These variables are destroyed as soon as the method completes.\r\n		</p>\r\n	</li>\r\n    <li>\r\n		<p>\r\n			<b>Instance variables</b> : Instance variables are variables declared within a class but outside any method.\r\n			These variables define the features of the class.\r\n		</p>\r\n	</li>\r\n    <li>\r\n		<p>\r\n			<b>Class variables</b> : Class variables are Instance variables, with a static keyword.\r\n			In other words they are unique for all objects belonging to the particular class.\r\n		</p>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>\r\n	To be able to use a variable, we need to define it with a name and a data type (or a class), known as <b>variable declaration</b>.\r\n	When we give a value to the variable, it is <b>variable initialization</b>.\r\n</p>\r\n<pre><code class=\"language-java\">int count;	//declaration with a data type\r\ncount = 1;	//initialization\r\nCar my_car; //declaration with class name\r\n\r\nint count2 = 2;	//declaration and initialization</code></pre>\r\n	\r\n<h5>Constructors in Java</h5>\r\n<hr/>\r\n<p>\r\n	Constructor is a special block of code in a class that defines the task that needs to be performed for every new object constructed.\r\n	Constructors may also use parameter values that are required for the initialization of the object.\r\n</p>\r\n<pre><code class=\"language-java\">public class Car {\r\n	Integer cost; //variable\r\n	String color; //variable\r\n		\r\n	//constructor\r\n	Car(String new_color, Integer new_cost) {\r\n		//initialize new object\r\n		cost = new_cost;\r\n		color = new_color;\r\n	}\r\n	\r\n	//function\r\n	public void drive(String destination, Integer velocity) {\r\n		//drive the car\r\n	}\r\n}</code></pre>\r\n\r\n<h5>Creating an Object</h5>\r\n<hr/>\r\n<p>\r\n	A new object is created in Java by referencing <b>new</b> keyword followed by constructor of the class of which the object is returned.\r\n	Generally the newly created object is stored in a variable of same class, as shown in the example.\r\n</p>\r\n<pre><code class=\"language-java\">Integer cost = 10;\r\nString color = \"black\";\r\n\r\nCar my_car;	//declaration with class name\r\nmy_car = new Car(color,cost); //pass variables as parameters to constructor\r\n//variable now contains a new object of Car Class</code></pre>','2018-04-30 12:35:12','2018-04-30 12:35:12'),('javafundamentals-understanding-jvm-jre-and-jdk','Understanding JVM, JRE and JDK',1,'final','tutorial','<p>\r\n    Java as a package includes three modules : JVM, JRE and the JDK. All the three modules are required in development compiling and running of a Java\r\n    application, yet all of them have independent functionalities.\r\n</p>\r\n<h5>\r\n    Java Virtual Machine (JVM)\r\n</h5>\r\n<hr/>\r\n<p>\r\n    The <code>.class</code> files (or the Java Byte code) produced after compiling <code>.java</code> files are not directly executable by the operating system,\r\n    instead they are run by the JVM which in itself runs on the OS as a distinct process.\r\n</p>\r\n<p>\r\n    Some of it\'s basic components are :\r\n</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n    <li>\r\n        <b>Class Loader : </b> The module responsible to read, verify, and initialize classes in an application along with it\'s dependencies.\r\n        It also initializes variables and allocates required memory and default values.\r\n    </li>\r\n    <li>\r\n        <b>Runtime Data Area : </b> It is a memory manager for the JVM. It keeps track of objects, methods, static variables, execution logs, PC registers etc.\r\n        essential during runtime of any application. It uses various data structures like heap for objects, variables; \r\n        stacks for each thread to track execution, and many more.\r\n    </li>\r\n    <li>\r\n        <b>Execution Engine : </b> Once a Java byte code is assigned with runtime data area, it is converted into native code (machine dependent byte code) \r\n        during runtime by Just-in-Time (JIT) compiler and an interpreter which are part of the Execution engine of the JVM. It is also responsible for \r\n        other important tasks like code optimization, garbage collection.\r\n    </li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<div class=\"row\">\r\n	<div class=\"col-md-6 offset-md-3\">\r\n		<img src=\"/Image/java-home-image\" class=\"img-thumbnail mx-auto\" />\r\n	</div>\r\n</div>\r\n<h5>\r\n    Java Run-time Environment (JRE)\r\n</h5>\r\n<hr/>\r\n<p>\r\n    Any Java application during run-time needs basic functionalities like standard input/output, printing service,\r\n    database connectivity (JDBC), user interface toolkits (AWT), compression (JAR), and many more. JRE is a collection or \r\n    <b>library</b> of such packages and classes which can be included and used by other Java applications without \r\n    worrying about it\'s implementation by the underlying operating system.\r\n</p>\r\n<p>\r\n    It should be understood that JRE is just a library and needs JVM for execution, so JRE cannot be installed without JVM.\r\n</p>\r\n<p>\r\n    JRE and JVM needs to be re-written for machines with different architecture and for different operating systems. \r\n    This makes Java a <b>portable programming language</b>. An application once compiled to Java byte code, can run on any other \r\n    machine (independent of the architecture) which has JRE and JVM installed.\r\n</p>\r\n<h5>\r\n    Java Development Kit (JDK)\r\n</h5>\r\n<hr/>\r\n<p>\r\n    It is understood that a compiled Java application only requires JRE and JVM to execute on any machine. \r\n    However, other important modules required for developing Java applications and producing compiled Java byte code like debugger, compiler (javac), etc\r\n    are provided. These modules including the JRE and the JVM is known as the complete Java Development Kit or the JDK.\r\n</p>\r\n<h5>\r\n    Should I Install JDK or JRE?\r\n</h5>\r\n<hr/>\r\n<p>\r\n    If you install JRE, it comes with JVM. Whereas, if you install JDK, it comes with JRE and JVM.\r\n</p>\r\n<p>\r\n    JVM is important for execution of Java byte code whereas JRE is an important library which provides basic functionalities \r\n    required by any Java application. JRE along with the JVM is always required. It is the extra packages provided by the JDK which is optional for \r\n    installation.\r\n</p>\r\n<p>\r\n    If you want to run Java applications or Java-dependent applications, JRE and JVM are sufficient, but to debug or compile java code, \r\n    JDK should also be installed. Since JDK needs JRE and JVM to function, JDK packages comes with JRE in it.\r\n</p>','2018-04-30 12:31:21','2018-04-30 12:31:21'),('javautilities-collections','Collections',1,'final','tutorial','<p>\r\n	JRE provides us <code>java.util.Collection</code> and it\'s various implementations to facilitate easy operations on \r\n	complex collections of objects like HashSet, LinkedList, etc.\r\n</p>\r\n<h5>\r\n	Java Collection Methods\r\n</h5>\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>\r\n	These methods can be called from any object of Collection sub-class (ArrayList, HashSet, etc).\r\n</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>\r\n		<h6><code>boolean add(Object element)</code></h6>\r\n		<p>\r\n			Insert element into the collection. Returns true on success.\r\n		</p>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		<h6><code>boolean addAll(Collection collection)</code></h6>\r\n		<p>\r\n			Adds all elements from the argument collection, to the caller collection object.\r\n			Returns true on success.\r\n		</p>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		<h6><code>boolean remove(Object element)</code></h6>\r\n		<p>\r\n			Removes element in the argument, from the caller collection object.\r\n			Returns true on success.\r\n		</p>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		<h6><code>boolean removeAll(Collection collection)</code></h6>\r\n		<p>\r\n			Removes all element values of the argument collection object, from the caller collection object.\r\n			Returns true on success.\r\n		</p>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		<h6><code>int size()</code></h6>\r\n		<p>\r\n			Returns int value representing the size of the collection object.\r\n		</p>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		<h6><code>void clear()</code></h6>\r\n		<p>\r\n			Removes all elements from the collection.\r\n		</p>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		<h6><code>boolean contains(Object element)</code></h6>\r\n		<p>\r\n			Returns true if the caller collection object contains the element value in the argument.\r\n		</p>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		<h6><code>boolean containsAll(Collection collection)</code></h6>\r\n		<p>\r\n			Returns true if the caller collection object contains all the element values from the argument collection object.\r\n		</p>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		<h6><code>Iterator iterator()</code></h6>\r\n		<p>\r\n			Returns it\'s iterator object.\r\n		</p>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		<h6><code>Object[] toArray()</code></h6>\r\n		<p>\r\n			Returns all it\'s elements as an object array.\r\n		</p>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		<h6><code>boolean isEmpty()</code></h6>\r\n		<p>\r\n			Returns true if collection contains no object.\r\n		</p>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		<h6><code>boolean equals(Collection collection)</code></h6>\r\n		<p>\r\n			Returns true if caller collection object and argument have equal values.\r\n		</p>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		<h6><code>int hashCode()</code></h6>\r\n		<p>\r\n			Returns hash code value for the collection object.\r\n		</p>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h5>\r\n	Java Collection Iterator\r\n</h5>\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>\r\n	Iterator class allows easy iteration through collection objects. It initially points to the first element in the collection.\r\n	Iterator object has following methods :\r\n</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>\r\n		<h6><code>Object next()</code></h6>\r\n		<p>\r\n			Moves pointer to next element and returns it.\r\n		</p>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		<h6><code>boolean hasNext()</code></h6>\r\n		<p>\r\n			Returns true if collection has more elements after the current.\r\n		</p>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		<h6><code>void remove()</code></h6>\r\n		<p>\r\n			Removes current element from the collection.\r\n		</p>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>\r\n	Consider following example :\r\n</p>\r\n<pre><code class=\"language-java\">List<Integer> intList = new List<Integer>();\r\nfor(int i=0; i<5; i++) {\r\n	intList.add(i);\r\n}\r\n\r\nIterator<Integer> intListIterator = intList.iterator();\r\nwhile(intListIterator.hasNext()) {\r\n	Integer element = (Integer)intListIterator.next();\r\n	System.out.print(element + \" \");\r\n}\r\n</code></pre>\r\n<p>\r\n	Output : \r\n</p>\r\n<pre><code class=\"language-java\">0 1 2 3 4</code></pre>','2018-04-30 12:43:13','2018-04-30 12:43:13'),('javautilities-date-and-time','Date and Time',1,'final','tutorial','<p>\r\n	JRE provides the <code>java.util.Date</code> class which can be used to perform various date and time related operations \r\n	in a java application.\r\n</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	New date object can be created using it\'s constructors :\r\n</p>\r\n<pre><code class=\"language-java\">Date currentDate = new Date();\r\nDate date2 = new Date(long milliseconds);</code></pre>\r\n<p>\r\n	Date constructor with empty arguments initializes the variable with current date and time, which the JVM requests from the operating system.\r\n	The other constructor accepts long type argument and initializes the variable with time exactly after number of milliseconds provided \r\n	since midnight, January 1, 1970. This time is fixed so time precise to a millisecond can be easily represented by a long variable.\r\n</p>\r\n<h5>\r\n	Java Date Methods\r\n</h5>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>\r\n		<h6><code>boolean after(Date date)</code></h6>\r\n		<p>\r\n			Return true if the time is greater than the given.\r\n		</p>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		<h6><code>boolean before(Date date)</code></h6>\r\n		<p>\r\n			Return true if the time is smaller than the given.\r\n		</p>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		<h6><code>Object clone()</code></h6>\r\n		<p>\r\n			Returns a duplicate object with same value.\r\n		</p>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		<h6><code>int compareTo(Date date)</code></h6>\r\n		<p>\r\n			Returns 0 if date is equal to the given date. Returns positive value if calling object is greater than the argument.\r\n			Returns a negative value if calling object is smaller than the argument.\r\n		</p>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		<h6><code>boolean equals(Date date)</code></h6>\r\n		<p>\r\n			Returns true if calling object has same value has argument.\r\n		</p>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		<h6><code>long getTime()</code></h6>\r\n		<p>\r\n			Returns number of milliseconds between the time and midnight, January 1, 1970.\r\n		</p>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		<h6><code>int hashCode()</code></h6>\r\n		<p>\r\n			Returns hash code value for the given date and time.\r\n		</p>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		<h6><code>void setTime(Long milliseconds)</code></h6>\r\n		<p>\r\n			Sets the object value with time, given milliseconds since midnight, January 1, 1970.\r\n		</p>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		<h6><code>String toString()</code></h6>\r\n		<p>\r\n			Returns string object with value including date and time of calling object.\r\n		</p>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h5>\r\n	Date to String formatting\r\n</h5>\r\n<p>\r\n	SimpleDateFormat class allows us to format date and time using predefined codes.\r\n</p>\r\n<pre><code class=\"language-java\">Date currentDate = new Date( );\r\nSimpleDateFormat dateFormat = new SimpleDateFormat(\"E dd.MM.yyyy hh:mm a\");\r\nSystem.out.println(\"Current Time : \" + dateFormat.format(currentTime));</code></pre>\r\n<p>\r\n	Output : \r\n</p>\r\n<pre><code class=\"language-none\">Current Time : Mon 14.05.2018 07:45 AM</code></pre>\r\n<p>\r\n	Similarly, other codes can be used : \r\n</p>\r\n<div class=\"row\">\r\n	<table class=\"table col-md-8 offset-md-2\">\r\n		<thead>\r\n			<tr>\r\n				<th>Character</th>\r\n				<th>Description</th>\r\n				<th>Example</th>\r\n			</tr>\r\n		</thead>\r\n		<tbody>\r\n			<tr>\r\n				<td>G</td>\r\n				<td>Era designator</td>	\r\n				<td>AD</td>	\r\n			</tr>\r\n			<tr>\r\n				<td>Y</td>\r\n				<td>four-digit year</td>	\r\n				<td>2018</td>	\r\n			</tr>\r\n			<tr>\r\n				<td>M</td>\r\n				<td>Month</td>	\r\n				<td>May</td>	\r\n			</tr>\r\n			<tr>\r\n				<td>d</td>\r\n				<td>two-digit day</td>	\r\n				<td>07</td>	\r\n			</tr>\r\n			<tr>\r\n				<td>h</td>\r\n				<td>Hour (12 hour format)</td>	\r\n				<td>08</td>	\r\n			</tr>\r\n			<tr>\r\n				<td>H</td>\r\n				<td>Hour (24 hour format)</td>	\r\n				<td>16</td>	\r\n			</tr>\r\n			<tr>\r\n				<td>m</td>\r\n				<td>2-digit minute</td>	\r\n				<td>52</td>	\r\n			</tr>\r\n			<tr>\r\n				<td>s</td>\r\n				<td>two-digit second</td>	\r\n				<td>09</td>	\r\n			</tr>\r\n			<tr>\r\n				<td>S</td>\r\n				<td>3-digit millisecond</td>	\r\n				<td>165</td>	\r\n			</tr>\r\n			<tr>\r\n				<td>E</td>\r\n				<td>String format day</td>	\r\n				<td>Friday</td>	\r\n			</tr>\r\n			<tr>\r\n				<td>w</td>\r\n				<td>week of year</td>	\r\n				<td>5</td>	\r\n			</tr>\r\n			<tr>\r\n				<td>W</td>\r\n				<td>week of month</td>	\r\n				<td>2</td>	\r\n			</tr>\r\n			<tr>\r\n				<td>a</td>\r\n				<td>AM/PM</td>	\r\n				<td>AM</td>	\r\n			</tr>\r\n			<tr>\r\n				<td>z</td>\r\n				<td>Time zone</td>	\r\n				<td>Eastern Standard Time</td>	\r\n			</tr>\r\n		</tbody>\r\n	</table>\r\n</div>','2018-04-30 12:43:02','2018-04-30 12:43:02'),('javautilities-numbers','Numbers',1,'final','tutorial','<p>\r\n	Java has primitive data types for numbers but JRE also provides us classes for Byte, Short, Integer, Long, Float, Double, \r\n	which has methods to perform number related operations with ease. All these classes implements <code>java.lang.Number</code>.\r\n</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	Java compiler automatically converts primitive data values into objects so that we can easily assign values to objects \r\n	without the new keyword. This is known as <b>boxing</b>. The compiler also converts object of above type into it\'s respective primitive \r\n	data type wherever needed, known as <b>unboxing</b>.\r\n</p>\r\n<pre><code class=\"language-java\">Integer i = 5; //boxing\r\n//i is unboxed, added to 2, and again boxed to j\r\nInteger j = i + 2;</code></pre>\r\n<h5>\r\n	Java Number Methods\r\n</h5>\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>\r\n	These methods can be called from any Number object (Short, Integer, Long, etc) :\r\n</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>\r\n		<h6><code>xxxx xxxxValue()</code></h6>\r\n		<p>\r\n			Converts the object value into xxxx data-type and returns the value in xxxx format.\r\n		</p>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		<h6><code>int compareTo(<i>dataType</i> value)</code></h6>\r\n		<p>\r\n			Returns positive value if caller object value is greater than argument. \r\n			Returns negative value if caller object value is smaller than argument. Returns 0 if value is same.\r\n		</p>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		<h6><code><i>dataType</i> pow(<i>dataType</i> base, <i>dataType</i> exponent)</code></h6>\r\n		<p>\r\n			Returns base value raised to power of exponent value.\r\n		</p>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		<h6><code>String toString()</code></h6>\r\n		<p>\r\n			Returns string object representing the value of the object.\r\n		</p>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ul>','2018-04-30 12:44:12','2018-04-30 